{
"content_id": "133183",
"reference_id": 109237,
"version": "1.0.4",
"title": "Job 2:11–3:26",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "18002011-18003026",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>Job’s friends Eliphaz, Bildad and Zophar visited him in order to comfort him. These men joined Job in his sadness. They recognised how terribly Job was suffering.</p><p>They did several things that were common in that time for people who were mourning. They also showed their respect for Job by being silent for <span data-bnType=\"resourceReference\" data-resourceId=\"108214\" data-resourceType=\"BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms\">seven</span> days. They waited for Job to speak first.</p><p>His speech was recorded as a long <span data-bnType=\"resourceReference\" data-resourceId=\"108204\" data-resourceType=\"BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms\">poem</span>. Job described how sad and bitter his life had become. He didn’t have any <span data-bnType=\"resourceReference\" data-resourceId=\"108211\" data-resourceType=\"BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms\">peace</span> or <span data-bnType=\"resourceReference\" data-resourceId=\"108212\" data-resourceType=\"BiblicaStudyNotesKeyTerms\">rest</span>. He wished that he hadn’t been born.</p><p>Job wondered why God allowed people who were suffering to continue living.</p>",
